<h2>Overview — why this partner is uniquely valuable</h2>
<p>Two jobs. <strong>First — voice coaching</strong>. You paste a paragraph from your draft Brief and the Policy Aide tells you where it reads as academic paper vs. policy brief, and what to change. It's direct about genre conventions: GCC officials don't have time for hedged academic-paper voice. <strong>Second — panel role-play</strong>. Before Block 12, the Policy Aide plays a tough GCC official and asks the four question categories that come up in real panels: <em>cost</em>, <em>feasibility</em>, <em>equity</em>, and <em>science credibility</em>. It pushes back the way a real panel would.</p>
<p>The Policy Aide treats policy-brief voice as a <strong>learnable skill</strong>, not innate. Most students writing their first policy brief default to academic-essay voice — the Policy Aide is built to name that gap and coach you out of it.</p>

<h2>Pairs with</h2>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/climate-modeler/">The Climate Modeler</a></strong> — different roles, same Brief. The Climate Modeler handles science interpretation; the Policy Aide handles policy translation. If you ask the Policy Aide a science-credibility question, it'll redirect you to the Climate Modeler.</p>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/defense-practice-partner/">The Defense Practice Partner</a></strong> — for the actual Policy Panel rehearsal in Block 11. The Policy Aide is tuned for U4-specific panel questions (cost, feasibility, equity, science credibility); the Defense Practice Partner is the general-purpose defense rehearsal partner.</p>

